The Comprehensive Plan provides policies relative to commercial development, orderly land
use transition and residential use compatibility. The relevant policies are analyzed below.
Policy 1-1.1.1: Protect Residential Areas From Incompatible Development
The Property and some of the adjacent land have been historically developed with
commercial and mixed uses for decades. Over time, the block of highway-fronting parcels
between South Hammock Road and Russell Street has transitioned from a mix of both
residential and commercial uses to a more predominant commercial uses and characteristics.
The remainder of the surrounding developed land exhibits a stable residential character.
There is not proposal to increase the nonresidential floor area on the Property from that
which currently exists. The Proposed Development would not further encroach into the
established residential area and would be consistent with Comprehensive Plan Policy 1-1.1.1.
Policy 1-1.1.2: Ensure Orderly Land Use Transition
To help ensure an orderly land use transition between residential and commercial uses, a 20-
foot-wide landscape bufferyard is required along the entire rear and side property lines
between the HC and R1 Zoning Districts. As submitted, the plans indicate an eight-foot-high
CMU wall to be constructed and located along the entire rear and side property lines
providing a further buffer between the two uses. The northwest corner of the Property
includes the loading dock area and trash compactor. A temporary sewage treatment system
would also be located in this area (Lot 2), if needed, until municipal wastewater is available.
The proposed loading docks and trash compactor area are not fully enclosed, but would be
screened on three sides by the building’s exterior concrete walls and mostly covered by the
Policy 1-2.1.9: Promote Low and Medium Intensity and Varied Commercial Designations
The intensity of commercial uses can be measured using trip generation in terms of traffic
volume per 1,000 square feet of floor area. The Village Code defines “medium intensity” as a
nonresidential use that generates between 50 and 100 average daily trips per 1,000 square
feet of floor area. According to the Applicant’s Level III traffic study dated July 2014 by
Crossroads Engineering Data Inc., the Proposed Development would generate 63.8 daily trips
per 1,000 square feet of floor area, which would be classified as a medium intensity use. The
Proposed Development of a supermarket and retail would be consistent with Comprehensive
Plan Policy 1-2.1.9, which encourages the promotion of general retail sales and services
designed to meet the needs for goods and services of local residents and Village visitors.
Policy 1-2.4.1: Guide the Location of Commercial Uses and Revitalize Commercial Areas
The previously-developed Property does not contain environmentally sensitive areas and is
considered disturbed with exotics habitat. The Proposed Development would revitalize an
existing commercial area where several businesses have been vacated for years. The scale
and intensity of the Proposed Development is in compliance with the HC Zoning District
standards. Cyclist and pedestrian movements would be promoted through the improvement
of the Overseas Heritage Trail, the provision of five covered bicycle racks, a sidewalk
between the Overseas Heritage Trail and the main entrance, and northbound and southbound
bus pullouts for the Dade-Monroe Express bus route. The Proposed Development would not
encroach into the established residential neighborhood and would be consistent with

historically has been commercially developed and is surrounded by land that has contained a

(4) The design of the proposed conditional use minimizes adverse effects, including visual

page.text: The Applicant has minimized adverse effects on adjacent lands through the use of
landscaping, an eight-foot CMU wall and the building’s design. The Property currently
contain six (6) separate driveways to U.S. 1 that would be eliminated and replaced with one
new driveway to U.S. 1 and one new access point on Russell Street that only provides ingress

Russell Street access point is designed solely for the ingress and egress for servicing the trash
compacter and the LP/diesel tanks. Russell Street serves both an adjacent school/church and
a residential area with seven homes.

Village of Islamorada - Monroe County, Florida

page.text: The site assessment and survey of the subject property was conducted initially during the week of
January 16, 2012 by the undersigned. Since then, several revisions to the site plan have occurred.
On September 23, 2013 the undersigned conducted a field review and re-marked as necessary, any
previously identified and marked trees. The proposed development parcel was made up of five
platted lots, but in early 2014 an additional lot of land was added to the east side. This Survey was
conducted on the added lot on February 17, 2014. The added lot was once the location of the
Islamorada Fish Bowl, a bowling alley with shops and parking areas. The six lots of the Parcel are
contiguous to one another and are located near mile marker 83 on the Overseas Highway in the
Florida Keys. The zoning district for all lots is “Highway Commercial” or HC. Total area of the
Parcel is 4.73+/- acres fronting on the Overseas Highway to the south side, Russell Street on the
west and a common boundary with several residences and undeveloped lots on the north side. To
the east of the parcel is a residential (R1) zoning district. The subject parcel is currently developed
with commercial buildings and parking areas. Open space is currently vegetated with exotic
vegetation and scattered native plants and trees. The parcel vegetative habitat on the six lots
fronting the Overseas Highway is classified as “Disturbed-740.0”.
In addition to the overall survey or inventory of plants, the parcel was inspected for vegetation
listed as threatened or endangered, of special concern, protected, regionally important, and
commercially exploited. Any wetlands located on the parcel were to be delineated and documented
by mapping. There are no wetlands identified on the parcel. The Village’s “Wetland Lot List” was
accessed to derive information as to any known wetland occurrence or scoring from the KEYWEP
or Florida Keys Wetlands Evaluation Procedure on the subject lot. This research proved negative
in results. The Village and Monroe County Protected Animal Species maps including the US Fish
& Wildlife habitat mapping were accessed and showed no zones of known critical habitat and
potential for the Eastern Indigo Snake and the Stock Island Tree Snail. This survey could not
identify any imperiled animal habitat or observations on the subject six lot parcel.
View of Some of the Existing Development on Overseas Hwy Typical Native Large Trees on the Developed Parcel
The parcel contains mostly isolated native hardwood hammock species that were either once
hammock remnants or planted as landscaping for the various commercial developments. The
Highway frontage lots of the subject parcel have large Gumbo Limbo, West Indies Mahogany,
Inkwood, and Green Buttonwood canopy trees as dominant vegetation. As development has
occurred in the past, landscaping and required planting around parking areas and buffers has
introduced other native and exotic plant species that are mixed with the larger hardwood trees.
There are smaller native plants found in the existing bufferyards of the parcel that were historically
planted for development landscaping. Typical of this category are the Paradise Tree, Lignum
Vitae, Jamaica Caper, Florida Thatch Palms, Sabal Palms, Pitch Apple, and Silver Buttonwood
trees. Invasive exotic plants are diverse and numerous in the open areas of the parcel. There are
areas with dense and out-of-control invasions completely displacing native plants. Some
mechanical mowing has kept the developed area open of understory and ground cover vegetation.
There are no indications of functional wetlands or seasonal wetlands on this multi-lot parcel.
There are mature native woody trees and bushes on the property. In accordance with the Village
Land Development Regulations, any native plant that measures 3.5 inches or greater in diameter at
breast height (DBH) requires mitigation by transplanting or other means if impacted by use or
development of the land. This measured tree is called a “Regulated Tree”. The survey identifies
these trees and locates them with their DBH in inches on the Survey Map of the parcel attached to
this survey report. Each plant that meets these criteria is marked with orange tree marking paint
visible at eye level from the Highway side of the parcel.
As with any property or development in Florida, invasive exotic vegetation is a real problem for the
owner. The State of Florida - Pest Plant Council has compiled a listing of the most threatening
exotic plants on the natural environment or what they refer to as Class I invasive exotic pest plants.
Those with only a potential to get out of control are given a Class II designation. All plants listed
as Invasive Exotics (Sec 30-1616(k)(3) must be eradicated from the property as a condition of
development. The Code requires continual maintenance to control the pest species by the property
owner after any eradication measure. These pest plants are identified generally on the Survey Map
by a triangle symbol with a letter symbol representing the invasive species found. The species
present are listed on the inventory below in this report.

page.text: There are State and Federal listed plants - threatened, endangered, regionally important, or
protected species found on this parcel. They are listed below in the inventory. Each listed plant is
also measured, marked with orange tree paint or flagging and mapped as to location and size. They
are inventoried by both DBH and height in feet - if a “listed” plant and small in size. Several of the
listed trees are large in size but none meet the criteria to categorize them as champion or specimen
trees. The protected (listed) species breakdown is: 6 Endangered Species, 3 Threatened, and 4
Regionally Important species. Numbers of plants in these categories are located on the maps and in
the Mitigation Plan. These plants are required to be mitigated for if impact occurs to them from
any proposed development. A review of the Village’s and Monroe County’s “Protected or
Endangered Species Maps” revealed no known wildlife habitat issues or zones and only a probable
occurrence of the Eastern Indigo Snake and the Schaus Butterfly for the subject lot. There is some
suitable browse or foraging of vegetative habitat but no cover habitat for nesting or natural uses for
wildlife. Human activity impact is high on the parcel and affects any use by wildlife. During this
survey work on the lot, there were signs of birds using the vegetation for forage or resting. A Gray
Squirrel and several species of butterflies were also noted. No signs of - or existing sitings of
arboreal snails were observed on the native or exotic trees. No critical habitat noted.

page.text: The subject parcel of six lots is highly disturbed with development and invasive exotics and the
vegetative habitat can only be classified as “Disturbed” 740. The commercial properties and a
single family residence that make up the parcel fronting on the Overseas Highway are each
developed with minimal and sparse native vegetation existing. Some rare or listed plants have been
planted as part of the past development buffering and set back planting requirements. Others have
been introduced naturally by birds and wind. Exotic and invasive exotic vegetation on this parcel is
the dominant plant species over the native woody species in the open spaces. Native trees found on
the parcel are remnants of past hammock or have been planted as landscaping or buffer
requirements for development. There are eleven different species of invasive exotic plants found
growing with some creating a dense overgrown canopy that prevents native plants from growing.
The front or highway side is scarified with clusters of native trees and very little understory or
ground cover. Exotic and native grasses that are mowed as lawn areas between parking areas and
on the buffer strips form primary ground cover. There are six different endangered species, three
threatened and four Regionally Important species found growing on the parcel. No significant
signs or observations of wildlife using this parcel for habitat and no mapped known or probable
critical wildlife habitat zones mapped by the Village in the area of this parcel were noted. US Fish
& Wildlife background overlay maps show potential for the Eastern Indigo Snake, and the Schaus
Butterfly habitat. No critical habitat for imperiled animals was noted. There are no champion or
specimen trees and none that meet the criteria of the Village of Islamorada which was established
for the protection of large trees.
Note: The habitat of the six lot parcel that is subject to this Survey is classified as “Disturbed-
740.0” vegetation. While there are native plants found on the parcel, as combined they cannot be
categorized as tropical hardwood hammock or other classifiable vegetative habitat. Therefore, a
“Habitat Analysis” is not indicated or recommended for this parcel.
